Quassinoids are triterpenoids biogenetically derived from (20
R
)- euphol or (20
S
)-tirucallol in the Simaroubaceae family of plants (Fiaschetti1 et al., 2011,
; Hou¨el et al., 2013). The transformation from triterpenes to quassinoids was accomplished by multi-step oxidative degradation (
). Quassinoids were categorized into 6 groups: C 26 , C 25 , C 20 , C 22 , C 19 and C 18 types
( Fig. 1 ), based on the carbon backbone (
,
).

Since the discovery of quassinoids, the study indicated that quassinoids display a wide range of biological and pharmacological effects, including antitumor, antimalarial, anti-inflammatory, antifeedant, insecticidal, amoebicidal, antiulcer and herbicidal activities (Fiaschetti1 et al., 2011). Nevertheless, due to serious toxicity (hypotension, nausea, vomiting and fever) and poor efficacy, the clinical trials of bruceantin ( 212 ) was failed (
;
, L et al., 1982).

There are several key reviews focusing on quassinoids (Fiaschetti1 et al., 2011, Hou¨el et al., 2013;
;
,
,
); however, there are no comprehensive review has been published in the past decade. In 2019, Li and coworkers have written a review on the quassinoids from 2004 to 2018, but only discussed in relation to the phytochemistry and plants sources of 190
quassinoids ( Li et al., 2019 )
. To date, the phytochemistry of quassinoids has made considerable progress, and 482 quassinoids were obtained. Moreover, longifolactone A ( 1) and longifolactone B ( 2 ) are the first members of a new class of quassinoids with an unusual C 26 carbon skeleton (
). The discovery not only enriches the structural diversity of quassinoids, but also has provide firm evidence of the biogenetic process from triterpenoid precursors to quassinoids. Moreover, pharmacological activities of quassinoids have also been further studied, especially their anticancer effects. The phytochemistry, anti-tumor activity, plant sources and biosynthesis of quassinoids during the last decades are covered in this review.

All quassinoids are believed to be biosynthesized through the triterpenoid biogenetic pathway, similar to that of the limonoids, another group of naturally occurring terpenoids (
). As natural product, the quassinoids have been elaborated in living organisms by complex enzyme systems developed over a long process of evolution. As shown in Fig. 1 , quassinoids are triterpenoids biogenetically derived from (20
R
) apo-euphol or (20
S
) apo-tirucallol. One of the methyl groups at C-4 and four carbon atoms at the end of the side chain have been removed and carbons C-20 to C-23 have been converted to a γ -lactone ring. However, the detailed degradation process of C 30 triterpenoids to C 25 quassinoids has remained ambiguous due to the lack of relevant biogenetic intermediates obtains to date. Recently, the discovery of the two C 26 quassinoids 1 and 2 has provided new insight into understanding the oxidative degradation pathway of
quassinoids ( Yang et al., 2020 )
.

First, the postulated C 30 triterpenoid precursor (20
S
)-tirucallol could convert to (20
S
)-apotirucallol by undergoing oxidation and skeletal rearrangement. Subsequently, (20
S
)-apotirucallol may lose four terminal carbons of its side chain and undergo selective oxidation to generate C 26 quassinoid 1 with a 20
R
configuration. Furthermore, selective oxidation of the α- methyl group at C-4 could lead to the formation of primary alcohol 2 , which may be oxidized to yield a δ -keto-acid intermediate A . Decarboxylation of δ- keto-acid A could lead to the selective loss of the α- methyl group at C-4 and generate the C 25 quassinoids. The C 20 - and C 19 -quassinoids would be formed by cleavage of the C-13/C-17 bond, formation of the C 19 -compounds requiring the additional loss of carbon atom of C-16 (
). The C 18 skeleton differs from C 19 by loss of one carbon atom in ring A , probably due to a benzylic rearrangement resulting in ring contraction (
;
).

