Cancer is one of leading health hazards and the second leading cause of mortality worldwide. When bruceantin (212) was isolated from the stem bark of
Brucea antidysenteria
in 1975, its application in the treatment of cancer has attracted wide attention of scholars (
;
). In the past few years, several quassinoids from Simaroubaceae family have been demonstrated to possess antitumor and cytotoxicity activities.

Bruceantin (212) was isolated from the stem bark of
Brucea antidysenteria Mill.
and identified as the active ingredient of this tree used against cancer (
). In the following decades, many researchers have conducted extensive studies on the quassinoids which are the active ingredients of Simaroubaceae family. The studies on the cytotoxicity of quassinoids has been broadly complied in excellent reviews (Fiaschetti1 et al., 2011, Hou¨el et al., 2013). Bruceantin was the first quassinoid introduced in clinical trials. But due to toxicity (hypotension, nausea, vomiting and fever) and poor efficacy, these clinical trials failed (
;
, L et al., 1982). Nevertheless, the pharmacological activity and mechanism of quassinoids have attracted extensive attention. In 2011, G. Fiaschetti et al. made a detailed review of the pharmacological mechanism of quassinoids, including ailanthone (195), shinjulactone C (201), brusatol (210), bruceantin (212), brucein D (222), simalikalactone E (248), peninsularinone (332), 15-desacetylundulatone (385), 6 α -tigloyloxychaparrinone (388), shinjulactone B (458), and several other quassinoids (Fiaschetti1 et al., 2011).

Zhao L J et al. investigated that the apoptotic induced by dehydrobruceine B (277) in human lung cancer A549 and NCI–H292 cells (

). And the involvement of a mitochondria-mediate intrinsic pathway in the pro-apoptotic action of dehydrobruceine B was also reported (
Fig. 33
). The results showed that treatment with dehydrobruceine B decreased cell viability, induced apoptotic and blocked cell cycle at S phase. And they found that the dehydrobruceine B induced apoptosis is caused by mediating mitochondrial intrinsic pathway, which was evidenced by the loss of MMP, the release of cytochrome 
c
into cytosol, and the cleavage of caspase-9, -3 and poly (ADP-ribose) polymerase (PAPR) (

).
